{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Additional details on SHAP and Shapley values can be found in [70].",
    "Federated SHAPLet H be the number of clients involved in the federation, x i an input instance, and f (x i) the prediction to be explained.",
    "In this work, the model f (•) is an MLP-NN learnt in a federated fashion.",
    "Following the setup proposed in [21], the goal Algorithm 1 KernelSHAP algorithm, from [70].Require: R: reference dataset, where each instance is defined by M features; Require: f: predictive model; Require: x i: instance for which the prediction f (x i) needs to be explained; Output: Shapley values φ j, for j = 1,..., M. 1: Sample K coalitions z k ∈ {0, 1} M, with k ∈ {1,..., K }, from the possible coalitions that can be generated.",
    "A value of 1 means that the corresponding feature value is \"present\" and 0 that it is \"absent\".2:for k = 1,..., K do 3: Compute z k = h x (z k), where h x: {0, 1} M → R M maps a coalition of features into the original feature space.For example, a coalition z k = (0, 1, 0, 1) is transformed into an instance z k as follows: since the second and fourth features are present in the coalition z k, the corresponding values of z k are taken from the input instance x i."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
